><gtr:grantReference>ES/G022852/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Psychological work on social identity and intergroup relations has often disregarded particular definitions of social categories such as 'nation' in its focus on general identity processes. The award holder's doctoral thesis takes issue with this, focussing on anti-immigrant attitudes. It demonstrates that the relationship between national identification and prejudice towards immigrants is contingent on particular understandings of nationality, rather than being generic or inevitable.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The fellowship will support the further dissemination of this work to both academic and non-academic audiences. However, its main purpose is to prepare the ground for a more substantial research programme that could address two key areas of concern. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The first is to extend beyond the paradigm of prejudiced attitudes, which framed the initial research, to look at anti-immigrant mobilisations and practices that impact on the political process. The second is to inform current scholarly and public debates on the implications of migration and ethnic diversity for political and civic engagement. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Social psychology has not generally engaged in these debates to the extent that it could. Thus, developing a social identity approach that could speak adequately to such issues is timely and important.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>21792</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E54B8F73-90A7-415C-9059-B040D22F83D6</gtr:id><gtr:title>Indigenous Rights in Chile: National Identity and Majority Group Support for Multicultural Policies</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Political Psychology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/647270303a040966629ca7bbeb0493d7"><gtr:id>647270303a040966629ca7bbeb0493d7</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Pehrson S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa2fa2e8dd705</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>91F55CB5-4CCD-4CB4-BF9D-9B2FF2FA45D0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Who We Are and Who Can Join Us: National Identity Content and Entry Criteria for New Immigrants</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Social Issues</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/647270303a040966629ca7bbeb0493d7"><gtr:id>64727030